ese relationships and practices, and Hegel's model for them are often the interactions and rituals of the members of religious communities.The book's close readings reveal the ethical implications of Hegel's discussions of slavery, Greek tragedy, early modern culture wars, and confession and forgiveness. The book also illuminates how contemporary democratic thought and practice can benefit from Hegelian insights.Through its sustained engagement with Hegel's ideas about conflict and reconciliation, Hegel's Social Ethics makes an important contribution to debates about how to live well with religious and ethical disagreement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aConsciousness. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aReconciliation. 0aReligion and sociology. 0aSocial ethics. 0aSociologyxPhilosophy. 0aSpirit. 0aTruth. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAntigone.  aChristian theologians.  aEnlightenment.  aFaith.  aG. W. F. Hegel.  aGreek tragedy.  aPhenomenology of Spirit.  aabsolute spirit.  aaccountability.  aalienation.  aauthority.  abelief.  acommunity norms.  aconfession.  aconflict.  ademocracy.  ademocratic authority.  adiverse communities.  adivine law.  adomination.  aepistemology.  aethical implications.  aethics.  aforgiveness.  ahuman law.  ahuman personhood.  amen.  anaturalist view.  anormativity.  anorms.  aorganized community.  aphilosophy.  areciprocal authority.  areciprocal recognition.  arecognition.  areconciliation.  areligion.  areligious difference.  arestorative justice.  arituals.  aself-legislation.  aslavery.  asocial ethics.  asocial practices.  asolidarity.  aspirit.  atheory of knowledge.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z9783110